    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "To me, it's just standard Unix behavior. Unless otherwise specified on the command line, a program will wait for STDIN. This allows for pipelining. For instance, type `ruby`, `cat`, or `wc` on the command line, and they will hang, waiting for input, and keep taking input until they receive an EOF character. Which means you can pipe streams into these programs, such as \r\n```\r\necho \"pragma solidity ^0.4.20; contract Foo {}\" | solc --bin\r\n```",
